Part I - Ford GoBike Data Exploration 2019¶

by Kristina Klimenchuk¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for one month, February 2019.

def hist_scale(data,xlabel, ylabel, title):
    """Get the data and plot a scaled histogram with labels.

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with a specific column to plot.
      labels (str): A sequence of strings providing the labels for each wedge
      title(str): The title for the plot.


    Returns:
      histogram
    """

    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(matplotlib.ticker.ScalarFormatter())
    ax.set_xticks( np.geomspace(min(data), max(data),15).round());

    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)

    ax.axvline(

              color="#d98100",
              label="Median: " + str(int(data.median())),
              linestyle='--', linewidth=2
              )

    ax.axvline(
              x=data.mean(), color="#d98100",
              label="Mean: " + str(int(data.mean())),
              linestyle='-',
              linewidth=2
              )
    


    ax.legend()

    plt.show()

def plotting_histplot(data, title):
    """Get the data and plot histplot with median and mean

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with specific columns to plot.


    Returns:
      histplot
    """
    # Initalize a figure and axes
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=1, nrows=1)

    # Plot the data
    sb.histplot(data)
        
    axes.axvline(
              x=data.median(),
              color="#d98100",
              label="Median: " + str(int(data.median())),
              linestyle='--', linewidth=2
              )

    axes.axvline(
              x=data.mean(), color="#d98100",
              label="Mean: " + str(int(data.mean())),
              linestyle='-',
              linewidth=2
              )
    
    axes.set_title(title, size = 14)

    axes.legend()

    plt.show()

# Function for pie plot 
def plot_pie(data,labels, title):
    """Get the data and pie plot with labels

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with a specific numeric column to plot.
      labels (list): A sequence of strings providing the labels for each wedge
      title(str): The title for the plot.


    Returns:
      pie plot 
    """
    ax = plt.figure(figsize = (4.5,4.5))

    ax = plt.pie(data, labels = labels, 
                 autopct='%1.0f%%',startangle = 90, 
                 textprops={'fontsize': 13}  )
    
    plt.title(title, fontsize=15)

def countplot_h(data, title):
    """Get dataframe specific column and count the amount of each type, 
       and plot horizontal bars with labels.

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with specific columns to plot.
      title (str): The title for the plot.


    Returns:
      plot horizontal bars
    """
            
     # Plotting data
    ax = sb.countplot(y = data, order = data.value_counts().index,palette = "PuBuGn_d");
    
    # Set labels and legend
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=18)
    plt.rc('legend', fontsize=13)
    
    # Patches is everything inside of the chart
    for rect in ax.patches:
        # Find where everything is located
        height = rect.get_height()
        width = rect.get_width()
        x = rect.get_x()
        y = rect.get_y()

        # The height of the bar is the data value and can be used as the label
        label_text = f'{width:.0f}'

        # ax.text(x, y, text)
        label_x = x + width/2
        label_y = y + height/2

        # plot only when height is greater than specified value
        if height > 0:
            ax.text(
                label_x,
                label_y,
                label_text,
                ha='center',
                va='center',
                fontsize=14
                )
    
    ax.set_title(title, size = 14)
    plt.show()

def plot_bar_h(data, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    """Get the data and plot vertical bars

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with specific columns to plot.
      xlabel (str): The label for x axis.
      ylabel (str): The label for y axis.
      title (str): The title for the plot.


    Returns:
      plot bars
    """
    # Plotting data
    ax = data.plot.barh(figsize=(9,4))

    # Set labels and legend
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=15)
    
    #plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    ax.legend(loc='best')
    plt.rc('legend', fontsize=12)

    # Patches is everything inside of the chart
    for rect in ax.patches:
        # Find where everything is located
        height = rect.get_height()
        width = rect.get_width()
        x = rect.get_x()
        y = rect.get_y()

        # The height of the bar is the data value and can be used as the label
        label_text = f'{width:.0f}'

        # ax.text(x, y, text)
        label_x = x + width/2
        label_y = y + height/2

        # plot only when height is greater than specified value
        if height > 0:
            ax.text(
                label_x,
                label_y,
                label_text,
                ha='center',
                va='center',
                fontsize=13
                )

def stacked_bars_h (data, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """Get the data and plot horizontal stacked bars with title and labels

    Args:
      data (pandas DataFrame): The DataFrame with specific columns to plot.
      xlabel (str): The label for x axis.
      ylabel (str): The label for y axis.
      title (str): The title for the plot.

    Returns:
      plot horizontal stacked bars
    """
    ax = data.plot.barh(stacked=True, color=color[1:3])


    # Set labels and legend
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=13)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=13)
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=15)

    ax.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.rc('legend', fontsize=13)

    # Patches is everything inside of the chart
    for rect in ax.patches:
    # Find where everything is located
        height = rect.get_height()
        width = rect.get_width()
        x = rect.get_x()
        y = rect.get_y()

    # The height of the bar is the data value and can be used as the label
        label_text = f'{width:.0f}'

    # ax.text(x, y, text)
        label_x = x + width / 2
        label_y = y + height / 2

    # plot only when height is greater than specified value
        if height > 0:
            ax.text(label_x, label_y,
            label_text, ha='center',
            va='center', fontsize=13)

The structure of the dataset.¶

Data has 183412 rows and 16 columns. Data includes information about users, bike stations, duration of the rides. Information about users contains: user type( customer or subscriber), birth year, and gender.

The main features of interest in the dataset.¶

In this project, I will focus on user-related features: user_type, member_birth_year, and member_gender.

Features duration_sec, star - end time will help investigate users' behavior.

Quality issues¶

  1. The columns start_time and end_time have an object data type.
  2. The data contain unrealistic customers' birth years, such as 1878.
  3. Columns with null values
  4. The Data has redundant columns with latitude and longitude information.

Tidiness issues¶

  1. start_time and end_time columns contain date and time on one column
  2. Absent weekday column.
  3. Absent the customers' age column.

Cleaning Data¶

Cleaning all documented issues from the assessment section.

In [19]:

Issue #1: The columns start_time and end_time have an object data type.¶

Define: Date and time data have to be in DateTime format.

In [20]:
# Convert "start_time" and "end_time" to a date-time

df["end_time"] = pd.to_datetime(df["end_time"])

Issue #2: The data contain unrealistic customers' birth years, such as 1878.¶

Define: To avoid redundancy and outliers, we will use member_birth_year no less than the 1945 year.

In [21]:
# Use query() function to select data
df = df.query("member_birth_year > 1945.0")

Issue #3: Columns with null values.¶

Define: The columns contain null values. We will drop all null rows.

In [22]:

Issue #4: The Data has redundant columns with latitude and longitude information.¶

Define:In this case, latitude and longitude information is useless; we will drop those columns.

Define: Initiate weekday column.

Section 1: Univariate Exploration¶

In this section we will investigate distributions of individual variables. I will use the "Question-Visualization-Observations" framework throughout the exploration. This framework involves asking a question from the data, creating a visualization to find answers, and then recording observations after each visualisation.

Who are Ford GoBike users?¶

  • What is the ratio of the users' type? What is the primary group "Customer" or "Subscriber"?
  • What is the primary users' gender?
  • How the distribution of users' age looks?

We will use the following features to answer those questions: user_type, member_gender, member_age.

What is the ratio of the users' type? What is the primary group "Customer" or "Subscriber"?¶

We will use a pie plot to determine which type of users is more significant.

In [29]:
# Use the plot_pie function to plot the ratio of the user types
plot_pie(df.user_type.value_counts(),df.user_type.value_counts().index, "The ratio of the user types")

The pie plot shows that 91% of users are subscribers, and only 9% describe customers.

What is the primary users' gender?¶

To count every type of gender in the dataset, we will use a horizontal bar plot.

In [30]:
# Use the countplot_h function to discover gender proportion
countplot_h(df.member_gender, "Gender of users")

The count plot shows that most users are males, which is 130207 users or 75%. Females have 23% or 40756 users, and others make up 2%.

How the distribution of users' age looks?¶

A histogram is the best way to show distribution. Also, I added average and median values to the plot.

In [31]:
# Use plotting_histplot() function to plot age distribution
plotting_histplot(df['member_age'], "Distribution of customers' age")

The histogram plot shows that most users' ages are between 25 and 35 years old. Meanwhile, the average age is 34 years old, and the median is 32 years old.

How do users use Ford GoBike service?¶

  • How long are trips duration?
  • What day of week and time of day do users prefer mostly?
  • What are the users' favorite stations?

How long are rides duration?¶

The data has a column of duration, which is measured in seconds. To see the duration of all rides, we will also use a histogram, but we have to use scaling for better visualization.

In [32]:
# Use hist_scale function to build duration distribution
hist_scale(df['duration_sec'],
           xlabel = 'Duration (sec)', 
           ylabel = 'Number of Trips', 
           title ='Distribution of Trip Durations')

The distribution shows that the average trip duration is 704 sec or 11.7 min, and the median is 511 or 8.5 min. Durations of rides take on a vast range of values, from 61 seconds at the lowest to 84548 seconds at the highest.

What day of week and time of day do users prefer mostly?¶

In the cleaning section, we added a new column with a day of weeks. And now we will count what day is more popular.

In [33]:
# Use countplot_h function

The most popular day is Thursday. Less popular are Sunday and Saturday.

What time do users usually start and end rides?¶

In [34]:
# Use plotting_histplot() function to plot start time distribution

The start time of rides histogram shows two spikes around 8-9 am and 5-6 pm

Since the average ride duration is 511 sec or 8,5 min, the end time rides are expected at the same hours with start time, 8-9 am and 5-6 pm. It is exactly what we can observe in the plot.

'start_station_name' and 'end_station_name' contain 329 unique stations. We will use plot_bar() function to count and plot 10 most popular station.

Conclusions¶

To investigate the questions about users and how they use the Ford GoBike service, we used several plots: pie, count, bars, histogram, and scaled histogram.

We found that 91% of users are subscribers, 75% (or 130207) are males. The age distribution is close to a normal distribution with 34 years old on average and 32 years old on a median. The range of distribution is 18 to 73 years old.

When I built a histogram for rides duration, I noticed that most rides lie under 1000 seconds, which causes the distribution to be skewed, with most of the distribution crowded into a small part of the graph. Hence, it's hard to tell where the median or mean should be on the histogram. I put the x-axis on a log scale to make the histogram more informative to solve this problem. As a result, we have a median ride of 511 seconds and an average ride of 704 seconds.

One of the things that surprised me is that most rides occur on Thursday and the less popular days are Saturday and Sunday.

Section 2: Bivariate Exploration¶

This section will investigate relationships between pairs of variables in data that we covered in the previous section (univariate exploration).

  • What is the users' type ratio in each gender?
  • What is the gender ratio by age? -What is the distribution of average duration rides by age?
  • Who makes the longer average ride customer or subscribers?
  • What days of the week are the most extended rides? -In what start time do users make the most duration?

What is the users' type ratio in each gender?¶

We need group member_gender by user typegroupby(), count it, and plot with stacked bars to answer that question.

What is the gender ratio by age?¶

We will build violion plot(sb.violinplot()) to explore how users' age is distributed by gender.

What days of the week are the most extended rides?¶

Weekdays have the most trips, and we will observe on which day users enjoy the longest ride.

In [46]:

In [47]:
# Plotting bar plot of average ride duration by days of the week
order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']

# Set labels and legend

ax.legend(loc='best')
plt.rc('legend', fontsize=13)

# Patches is everything inside of the chart
for rect in ax.patches:
# Find where everything is located
    height = rect.get_height()
    width = rect.get_width()
    x = rect.get_x()
    y = rect.get_y()

    # The height of the bar is the data value and can be used as the label
    label_text = f'{height:.0f}'

    # ax.text(x, y, text)
    label_x = x + width/2
    label_y = y + height/2

    # plot only when height is greater than specified value
    if height > 0:ax.text(
                label_x,
                label_y,
                label_text,
                ha='center',
                va='center',
                fontsize=13)

According to the bar plot, Saturday and Sunday have the most extended rides on average.

Conclusion¶

Subscriber users' type is the dominant type in each gender. The average age of each gender is in the same age group: 30 - 35 y.o. Also, the same age group has the most longest rides on average.

An interesting finding is that even though subscribers make up 91% of all users, their average trip is 640 seconds, while the average ride duration for customers is 1310 seconds.

In section 1 we talk that Saturday and Sunday are less popular days according to the number of rides. Nonetheless, weekends days have the most longer duration rides on average than days of the week. On weekdays, the average duration is 677 seconds and for the weekend equals 855 seconds.

Also, users make longer ride duration if they start rides between 7 and 9 am; and 5-6 pm.

Conclusion¶

If we look at the line plot, we can see that the average ride duration among Subscribers does not change much depending on the days of the week. At the same time, the average ride duration among Customers rises sharply on weekends.

Summary¶

Original data has 183412 rows and 16 columns. During assessment were detected four quality and three tidiness issues.

After fixing all issues shape of the data set contains 174582 rows and 12 columns. During the cleaning section, I dropped several columns such as station latitude longitude of start and end; stations id, because we have station names and it would be redundant keep all; etc.

In section 1 we investigated individual variables and found out that the average user of Ford GoBike is a male of 32-34 years old, a subscriber.

The less popular days of the week are Saturday and Sunday, but in section two, we discover that weekend has the most extended ride duration. That happens because the "Customer" users type uses the service mostly on weekends and have a long ride duration. While "Subscriber" takes the short ride on a working day and based on start time, I suggest it is a ride to work trip.

Limitation¶

The main limitation of the data set is that it is only one month data. We can't make a conclusion by month and seasonality based on this data. Also, I would like to see more users' data; each user, each ride, cost of a ride. That data would be convenient for business decisions.
